				<note resp="Philip Lampi">"Ephraim Kirby and John Welsh, Esqrs. are chosen by the Freemen to represent this town in the next General Assembly...and brought together 394 voters.  A fuller house was never known."  The Monitor (Litchfield, CT).  September 18, 1799.</note>
				<note resp="Philip Lampi">"In Litchfield, a strong hold of federalism, on our late fall election, the republican interest gained a decisive and important victory.  The leading candidates were Messrs. Kirby and Allen.  And on the poll the statement of votes was thus -- whole number 395, of whom Mr. Kirby had 265, or 185 more than all the other candidates together.  Mr. Welsh who was left out of the commission as a justice, at the last session of the assembly, for taking the BEE, and other similar offences, is the second deputy."  Aurora. General Advertiser (Philadelphia, PA).  November 6, 1799.</note>
